    {
      "id": 361503,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>The following reactivity order has been found for the basic hydrolysis of <i>p</i>-substituted methyl benzoates:</p>\n<p>Y=NO<sub>2</sub> &gt; Br &gt; H &gt; CH<sub>3</sub> &gt; OCH<sub>3</sub></p>\n<p>How can you explain this reactivity order? Where would you expect Y=C<span data-math=\"\\text{≡}\"></span>N, Y=CHO, and Y=NH<sub>2</sub> to be in the reactivity list?</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBa2dYIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--80b740280520b7c4c3ef028a1b76a429db686239/OChem_21_EC_049.jpg\" alt=\"Reaction of a para-substituted methyl benzoate with aqueous base to give the corresponding carboxylate ion and methanol. The substitutent at the para position is represented by the letter Y.\">",
